{
  "texts": [
    "The observed similarity score ρ is drawn from some distribution f (ρ|x).",
    "If researchers had access to labeled examples-cases where x = 1 or x = 0 was independently verified-they could estimate these conditional distributions and compute P (x = 1|ρ).",
    "However, in many real-world settings, such labeled data are limited or incomplete, making it challenging to quantify measurement error or assess the reliability of similarity-based conclusions.",
    "But constructing such labeled gold standard is far from straightforward.",
    "It is clear that two identical text documents should be assigned a similarity of 1, but for similar, yet not identical, artifacts, there is no obvious way-even in principle-to determine the gold-standard value for x (if such a standard even exists)."
  ]
}